  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do I have red itchy balls all over my skin?",
  "response": "Red, itchy bumps on your skin can be caused by a variety of factors. Here are some common reasons:\n\n1. **Hives (Urticaria):** Often caused by an allergic reaction to food, medication, or other allergens. Stress or infections can also trigger hives.\n\n2. **Eczema (Atopic Dermatitis):** A chronic condition that causes dry, itchy skin and rashes. It can be triggered by irritants, allergens, or stress.\n\n3. **Contact Dermatitis:** This occurs when your skin comes into contact with an irritant or allergen, such as certain soaps, detergents, or plants like poison ivy.\n\n4. **Insect Bites:** Bites from mosquitoes, bed bugs, or other insects can cause red, itchy bumps.\n\n5. **Heat Rash (Miliaria):** Common in hot, humid weather, this rash is caused by blocked sweat ducts.\n\n6. **Folliculitis:** An infection of the hair follicles, often caused by bacteria or fungi, which can result in itchy, red bumps.\n\n7. **Scabies:** Caused by tiny mites burrowing into the skin, leading to intense itching and a pimple-like rash.\n\n8. **Psoriasis:** A chronic skin condition that speeds up the life cycle of skin cells, causing red, itchy, scaly patches.\n\nIf the bumps persist, worsen, or are particularly bothersome, it's a good idea to consult a healthcare professional for a proper diagnosis and treatment. They might recommend antihistamines, topical creams, or other medications depending on the cause.",
